# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: conflagration
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:conflagration/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] The **1866 great fire of Portland** was a large fire that spread throughout the city of Portland, Maine, on July 4, 1866—the second Independence Day after the end of the American Civil War.
[src:conflagration/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] The fire burned out the morning of July 5; while over a thousand buildings were destroyed, there were few fatalities.
[src:conflagration/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] Occurring five years before the Great Chicago Fire, it was the greatest fire yet seen in an American city.
[src:conflagration/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] The fire started in a boat house near today's Hobson's Wharf on Commercial Street, likely caused by a firecracker or a cigar ash.
[src:conflagration/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] The fire spread to a lumber yard and on to a sugar house, then spread across the city, eventually burning out early the next morning on Munjoy Hill in the city's east end.
[src:conflagration/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] Four people died in the fire and 10,000 people were made homeless.
[src:conflagration/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] Around 1,800 buildings (1,200 homes) were burned to the ground, including the first of three city halls which have stood at the present Congress Street location.
[src:conflagration/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] Also lost was the federal Exchange Building, which was replaced with the custom house.
[src:conflagration/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] Soon after the fire, Portland native and acclaimed poet Henry Wadsworth Longfellow described his old home town: "Desolation, desolation, desolation.
[src:conflagration/1866-great-fire-of-portland-maine] It reminded me of Pompeii, that 'sepult city.'" More than 600 buildings were constructed in the four months following the fire.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] The **1900 Hoboken Docks fire** occurred on June 30, 1900, and killed at least 326 people in and around the Hoboken, New Jersey piers of the Norddeutscher Lloyd (NDL) shipping company.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] The piers were in New York Harbor, at the foot of 3rd and 4th Streets in Hoboken, across the North River (Hudson River) from Manhattan in New York City.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] The area, a few blocks north of Hoboken Terminal, is now mostly part of the Hudson River, without docks: a waterfront bicycle path lines it.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] The fire began when cotton bales stored on NDL's southernmost wharf caught fire, and winds carried the flames to nearby barrels of volatile liquids, such as turpentine and oil, which exploded in rapid succession.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] It burned NDL's Hoboken piers to the waterline, consumed or gutted nearby warehouses, gutted three of NDL's major transatlantic liners, and damaged or destroyed nearly two dozen smaller craft.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] Most of the victims were seamen and other workers but included women visiting one of the ships.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] Many who died in the fires were interred at the Flower Hill Cemetery, North Bergen.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] The holder of the Blue Riband at the time of the fire, NDL's *Kaiser Wilhelm der Grosse*, was also docked in the company's Hoboken piers, but fared better than its sister ships.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] She was the first of the steamers that tugs tried to pull away from the pier (15 minutes after the fire began).
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] The fire erupted on a Saturday that was considered a “half-holiday” when no departures were scheduled.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] Had any of the ships been ready to sail, the loss of life and property would have been much greater.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] The fire also destroyed several Campbell Stores warehouses, built by the Hoboken Land & Improvement Company, the nearby piers of the Scandinavian America Line and a railroad shed.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] According to *The New York Times*, the railroad shed belonged to West Shore Railroad, although it was more likely a shed of Hoboken Shore Railroad (which connected the West Shore Railroad's lines at the Weehawken Terminal to the Hoboken docks).
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] A shed of Hamburg America Line was partly chopped down during the fire by the fire service to avoid spreading of the fire to the Hamburg America Line piers.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] The total value of property losses due to the fire was estimated (the morning after the fire) at $6.175 million, and (the following year) at $5.35 million.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] The NDL replaced its Hoboken piers with larger, stronger and more fireproof structures.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] The new steel piers were known as Hoboken Pier Nos.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] All of the damaged ocean liners returned to maritime service, *Saale* under a different name (the SS *J.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] On the first anniversary of the fire, a large granite monument was dedicated in Flower Hill Cemetery in North Bergen, New Jersey above a mass grave containing unidentifiable bodies of the victims, listing the names of the dead and missing.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] Others responded that making portholes larger would be cost-prohibitive, or come at the expense of structural strength.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] In the end, regulations required portholes to be big enough for a person of reasonable size to escape.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] In 1905, a fire consumed the Delaware, Lackawanna and Western Railroad's Hoboken ferry piers.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] The piers immediately south of the NDL piers, owned before World War I by Hamburg America Line, were later also destroyed by fire.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] In 1921, two of the three piers (Hoboken Pier Nos.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] 5 and 6) were consumed in a fire that also scorched the SS *Leviathan*.
[src:conflagration/1900-hoboken-docks-fire] 4 burned, killing three and briefly setting afire the SS *Nathaniel Alexander*, a Liberty ship.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] A magnitude 7.9 earthquake struck the coast of Northern California at 05:12 am Pacific Standard Time on Wednesday, April 18, 1906.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] With a maximum Mercalli intensity of XI (*Extreme*), it created high-intensity shaking from Eureka on the North Coast to the Salinas Valley, an agricultural region to the south of the San Francisco Bay Area.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Extensive fires soon broke out in San Francisco and lasted for several days.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] More than 3,000 people died and over 80% of the city was destroyed.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The event is remembered as the deadliest earthquake in the history of the United States.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The death toll remains the greatest loss of life from a natural disaster in California's history and high on the list of worst American disasters, natural or man-made.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The San Andreas Fault is a continental transform fault that forms part of the tectonic boundary between the Pacific plate and the North American plate.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The strike-slip fault is characterized by mainly lateral motion in a dextral sense, where the western (Pacific) plate moves northward relative to the eastern (North American) plate.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] This fault runs the length of California from the Salton Sea in the south to Cape Mendocino in the north, a distance of about 810 miles (1,300 km).
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The maximum observed surface displacement was about 20 feet (6 m); geodetic measurements show displacements of up to 28 feet (8.5 m).
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The 1906 earthquake preceded the development of the Richter scale.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The most widely accepted estimate for the magnitude of the quake on the modern moment magnitude scale is 7.9; values from 7.7 to as high as 8.3 have been proposed.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] According to findings published in the *Journal of Geophysical Research*, severe deformations in the Earth's crust took place both before and after the earthquake's impact.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Accumulated strain on the faults in the system was relieved during the earthquake, which is the supposed cause of the damage along the 280-mile-long (450 km) segment of the San Andreas plate boundary.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The 1906 rupture propagated both northward and southward for a total of 296 miles (476 km).
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Shaking was felt from Oregon to Los Angeles, and as far inland as central Nevada.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] A strong foreshock preceded the main shock by about 20 to 25 seconds.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The strong shaking of the main shock lasted about 42 seconds.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] There were decades of minor earthquakes – more than at any other time in the historical record for northern California – before the 1906 quake.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] For years, the epicenter of the quake was assumed to be near the town of Olema, in the Point Reyes area of Marin County, due to local earth displacement measurements.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In the 1960s, a seismologist at UC Berkeley proposed that the epicenter was more likely offshore of San Francisco, to the northwest of the Golden Gate.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The most recent analyses support an offshore location for the epicenter, although significant uncertainty remains.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] An offshore epicenter is supported by the occurrence of a local tsunami recorded by a tide gauge at the San Francisco Presidio; the wave had an amplitude of approximately 3 inches (7.6 cm) and an approximate period of 40–45 minutes.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Analysis of triangulation data before and after the earthquake strongly suggests that the rupture along the San Andreas Fault was about 310 miles (500 km) in length, in agreement with observed intensity data.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The available seismological data support a significantly shorter rupture length, but these observations can be reconciled by allowing propagation at speeds above the S-wave velocity (supershear).
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Supershear propagation has now been recognized for many earthquakes associated with strike-slip faulting.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In 2019, using an old photograph and a recorded eyewitness account, researchers were able to refine the location of the hypocenter of the earthquake as offshore from San Francisco or near San Juan Bautista, confirming previous estimates.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The shaking intensity as described on the Modified Mercalli intensity scale reached XI (*Extreme*) in San Francisco and areas to the north like Santa Rosa where destruction was devastating.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The most important characteristic of the shaking intensity noted in Andrew Lawson's 1908 report was the clear correlation of intensity with underlying geologic conditions.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Areas situated in sediment-filled valleys sustained stronger shaking than nearby bedrock sites, and the strongest shaking occurred in areas of former bay where soil liquefaction had occurred.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Modern seismic-zonation practice accounts for the differences in hazard posed by varying geologic conditions.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The main shock was followed by many aftershocks and some remotely triggered events.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] As with the 1857 Fort Tejon earthquake, there were fewer aftershocks than would have been expected for a shock of that size.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Very few of them were located along the trace of the 1906 rupture, tending to concentrate near the ends of the rupture or on other structures away from the San Andreas Fault, such as the Hayward Fault.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The only aftershock in the first few days of near MI 5 or greater occurred near Santa Cruz at 14:28 PST on April 18, with a magnitude of about 4.9 M.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The largest aftershock happened at 01:10 PST on April 23, west of Eureka with an estimated magnitude of about 6.7 MI, with another of the same size more than three years later at 22:45 PST on October 28 near Cape Mendocino.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Remotely triggered events included an earthquake swarm in the Imperial Valley area, which culminated in an earthquake of about 6.1 MI at 16:30 PST on April 18, 1906.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Another event of this type occurred at 12:31 PST on April 19, 1906, with an estimated magnitude of about 5.0 MI, and an epicenter beneath Santa Monica Bay.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Seismographs on the U.S. east coast recorded the earthquake some 19 minutes later.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Some early death estimates exceeded 500.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Early death counts ranged from 375 to over 500.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] However, hundreds of fatalities in Chinatown went ignored and unrecorded.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The total number of deaths is still uncertain, but various reports presented a range of 700–3,000+.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In 2005, the city's Board of Supervisors voted unanimously in support of a resolution written by novelist James Dalessandro ("1906") and city historian Gladys Hansen ("Denial of Disaster") to recognize the figure of 3,000+ as the official total.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Most of the deaths occurred within San Francisco, but 189 were reported elsewhere in the Bay Area; nearby cities such as Santa Rosa and San Jose also suffered severe damage.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Between 227,000 and 300,000 people were left homeless out of a population of about 410,000; half of those who evacuated fled across the bay to Oakland and Berkeley.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Newspapers described Golden Gate Park, the Presidio, the Panhandle and the beaches between Ingleside and North Beach as covered with makeshift tents.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] More than two years later, many of these refugee camps were still in operation.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The earthquake and fire left long-standing and significant pressures on the development of California.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] At the time of the disaster, San Francisco had been the ninth-largest city in the United States and the largest on the West Coast.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Over a period of 60 years, the city had become the financial, trade, and cultural center of the West, operating the busiest port on the West Coast.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] It was the "gateway to the Pacific", through which growing U.S. economic and military power was projected into the Pacific and Asia.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Over 80% of the city was destroyed by the earthquake and fire.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Though San Francisco rebuilt quickly, the disaster diverted trade, industry, and population growth south to Los Angeles, which during the 20th century became the largest and most important urban area in the West.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Many of the city's leading poets and writers retreated to Carmel-by-the-Sea where, as "The Barness", they established the arts colony reputation that continues today.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The 1908 Lawson Report, a study of the 1906 quake led and edited by Professor Andrew Lawson of the University of California, showed that the same San Andreas Fault which had caused the disaster in San Francisco ran close to Los Angeles as well.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The earthquake was the first natural disaster of its magnitude to be documented by photography and motion picture footage and occurred at a time when the science of seismology was blossoming.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Writing from San Francisco on April 23, five days after the earthquake, resident John W.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Nourse described the scene to his family in Indiana: woken at quarter past five by shaking that made the house "seem like it would break all to pieces," he looked out to see a large brick building completely destroyed in seconds, with fires visible simultaneously to the right, front, and left.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Grabbing the baby's buggy, he and his wife Lena fled to Market Street, which he described as a terrible sight.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Whole blocks reduced to masses of ruins, City Hall a complete wreck.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He left his wife and baby at the mission and returned to try to save their belongings, but found the whole part of the city burning.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] "In traveling over the city it looks like there is not a building but what is more or less damaged," he wrote.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] A traveler passing through San Francisco ten days after the earthquake, Mrs.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Baughman of LeMars, Iowa, described a stove placed in front of every house, residents were not permitted to cook indoors, and Market Street sunken several feet in places, with one point four blocks from the Ferry five feet lower than the sidewalk and the cable car rails warped and twisted.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] She observed soldiers with blue coats throughout the begrimed crowds, groups of listless dazed men in the suburbs, and frame buildings near Valencia Street completely shattered within a radius of several blocks.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Writing from Boulder Creek, eighty miles south of San Francisco, former journalist Mathias Forestburg described being violently awakened by the shaking, the house rocking like a boat with timbers creaking and everything thrown to the floor.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He spent the morning dismantling a cracked chimney that was balanced on three bricks.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] One more aftershock would have brought it down and demolished the house.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He reported continual shaking every day and night since the earthquake, keeping the community on constant alert, and noted that all business had stopped and all who could afford to leave were going east.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The most immediate firsthand account came from Lewis A.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Spitzer of San Jose, who wrote to his brother-in-law in Virginia at midnight on the day of the earthquake itself.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Spitzer had been staying at a mineral spring in the mountains the previous night; waking just before 5 AM, he was thrown against the wall at 5:15 as the shock struck while he was putting a pan of water on the stove.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Electric cars had stopped running and he hired a farmer to bring him home by buggy.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He found his house standing with only cracked plaster, but described San Jose as "in ruins.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Fine business houses flat on the ground" and San Francisco as nearly all in ruins and in flames.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] His son-in-law had arrived from San Francisco reporting that Spitzer's son and his wife and baby appeared to have escaped safely, but the family could not reach them.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The streets were full of people camping in tents, some without tents, afraid to go indoors.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] "I have seen many heart rending scenes in my life," he wrote, "but never any such a terrible scene as this.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Although the impact of the earthquake on San Francisco was the most famous, the earthquake also inflicted considerable damage on several other cities.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] These include San Jose and Santa Rosa, the entire downtown of which was essentially destroyed.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Duffy of Owensboro, Kentucky, who had been staying at the St.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Rose Hotel in Santa Rosa, reported being trapped for five hours in the ruins before rescuers reached him.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He finally made his location known by poking a lath through a hole left by a falling steam pipe.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] As damaging as the earthquake and its aftershocks were, the fires that burned out of control afterward were far more destructive.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] It has been estimated that at least 80%, and at most over 95%, of the total destruction was the result of the subsequent fires.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Within three days, over 30 fires, that were caused by ruptured gas mains, destroyed approximately 25,000 buildings on 490 city blocks.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The fires cost an estimated $350 million at the time (equivalent to $9.1 billion in 2024).
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The *Ham and Eggs* fire, in the morning on the 18th, at Hayes and Gough Streets, in Hayes Valley, was started by a woman who lit her stove to prepare breakfast, unaware of the badly damaged chimney, destroying a 30-block area, including a college, the Hall of Records and City Hall.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Some of the fires were started when San Francisco Fire Department firefighters, untrained in the use of dynamite, attempted to demolish buildings to create firebreaks.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The dynamited buildings often caught fire.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Sullivan, who would have been responsible for coordinating firefighting efforts, had died from injuries sustained in the initial quake.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In total, the fires burned for four days and nights.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Most of the destruction in the city was attributed to the fires, since widespread practice by insurers was to indemnify San Francisco properties from fire but not from earthquake damage.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Army Signal Corps reported that he "was stopped by a fireman who told me that people in that neighborhood were firing their houses...they were told that they would not get their insurance on buildings damaged by the earthquake unless they were damaged by fire".
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] One landmark building lost in the fire was the Palace Hotel, subsequently rebuilt, which had many famous visitors including royalty and celebrated performers.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] It was constructed in 1875 primarily financed by Bank of California co-founder William Ralston, the "man who built San Francisco." In April 1906, the tenor Enrico Caruso and members of the Metropolitan Opera Company came to San Francisco to give a series of performances at the Grand Opera House.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The night after Caruso's performance in *Carmen*, the tenor was awakened in the early morning in his Palace Hotel suite by a strong jolt.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Clutching an autographed photo of President Theodore Roosevelt, Caruso made an effort to get out of the city, first by boat and then by train, and vowed never to return.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The Metropolitan Opera Company lost all of its traveling sets and costumes.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Some of the greatest losses from fire were in scientific laboratories.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Alice Eastwood, the curator of botany at the California Academy of Sciences in San Francisco, is credited with saving the entire plant type specimen collection of the Academy before the remainder of the largest botanical collection in the western United States was destroyed in the fire.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The entire laboratory and all the records of Benjamin R.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Jacobs, a biochemist who was researching the nutrition of everyday foods, were destroyed.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The original California flag used in the 1846 Bear Flag Revolt at Sonoma, stored in a state building in San Francisco, was also destroyed in the fire.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Sullivan, was gravely injured when the earthquake first struck and later died from his injuries.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Sullivan and his wife had been sleeping in the engine house adjoining the California Hotel on Bush Street when bricks crashed through the roof.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The interim fire chief sent an urgent request to the Presidio for dynamite.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] General Frederick Funston had already decided that the situation required the use of federal troops.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Telephoning a San Francisco Police Department officer, he sent word to Mayor Eugene Schmitz of his decision to assist and then ordered federal troops from nearby Angel Island to mobilize and enter the city.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Explosives were ferried across the bay from the California Powder Works in what is now Hercules.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] During the first few days, soldiers provided valuable services like patrolling streets to discourage looting and guarding buildings such as the U.S.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] They aided the fire department in dynamiting to demolish buildings in the path of the fires.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The Army also became responsible for feeding, sheltering, and clothing the tens of thousands of displaced residents of the city.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Under the command of Funston's superior, Major General Adolphus Greely, Commanding Officer of the Pacific Division, over 4,000 federal troops saw service during the emergency.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Police officers, firefighters, and soldiers would regularly commandeer passing civilians for work details to remove rubble and assist in rescues.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] On July 1, 1906, non-military authorities assumed responsibility for relief efforts, and the Army withdrew from the city.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Accusations of soldiers engaging in looting also surfaced.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Retired Captain Edward Ord of the 22nd Infantry Regiment was appointed a special police officer by Schmitz and liaised with Greely for relief work with the 22nd Infantry and other military units involved in the emergency.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Ord later wrote a long letter to his mother on April 20 regarding Schmitz's "Shoot-to-Kill" order and some "despicable" behavior of certain soldiers of the 22nd Infantry who were looting.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He also made it clear that the majority of soldiers served the community well.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Property losses from the disaster have been estimated to be more than $400 million in 1906 dollars.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] This is equivalent to $10.4 billion in 2024 dollars.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] An insurance industry source tallies insured losses at $235 million, the equivalent to $6.13 billion in 2024 dollars.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Political and business leaders strongly downplayed the effects of the earthquake, fearing loss of outside investment in the city which was badly needed to rebuild.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The earthquake is not even mentioned in the statement.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Fatality and monetary damage estimates were manipulated.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Almost immediately after the quake (and even during the disaster), planning and reconstruction plans were hatched to quickly rebuild the city.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Rebuilding funds were immediately tied up by the fact that virtually all the major banks had been sites of the conflagration, requiring a lengthy wait of seven to ten days before their fire-proof vaults could cool sufficiently to be safely opened.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The Bank of Italy (now Bank of America) had evacuated its funds and was able to provide liquidity in the immediate aftermath.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Its president also immediately chartered and financed the sending of two ships to return with shiploads of lumber from Washington and Oregon mills which provided the initial reconstruction materials and surge.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Branner, who was the first to begin study of the San Andreas fault in 1891 complained that the Federal Government of the United States had not conducted the serious studies that were needed to gather data about earthquakes on the west coast.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He said public discussion was being stifled by fears that acknowledgement of earthquakes would drive away business and investors, and that geologists were told not to gather information about the 1906 earthquake, and certainly to not publish it.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Some people went as far as to deny that an earthquake had happened.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Eleven days after the earthquake a rare Sunday baseball game was played in New York City (which would not allow regular Sunday baseball until 1919) between the Highlanders (soon to be the Yankees) and the Philadelphia Athletics to raise money for quake survivors.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] William James, the pioneering American psychologist, was teaching at Stanford at the time of the earthquake and traveled into San Francisco to observe first-hand its aftermath.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] He was most impressed by the positive attitude of the survivors and the speed with which they improvised services and created order out of chaos.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] This formed the basis of the chapter "On some Mental Effects of the Earthquake" in his book *Memories and Studies*.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Wells had just arrived in New York on his first visit to America when he learned of the San Francisco earthquake.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] What struck him about the reaction of those around him was that "it does not seem to have affected any one with a sense of final destruction, with any foreboding of irreparable disaster.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Every one is talking of it this afternoon, and no one is in the least degree dismayed.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] I have talked and listened in two clubs, watched people in cars and in the street, and one man is glad that Chinatown will be cleared out for good; another's chief solicitude is for Millet's *Man with a Hoe*.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] 'They'll cut it out of the frame,' he says, a little anxiously.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] 'Sure.' But there is no doubt anywhere that San Francisco can be rebuilt, larger, better, and soon.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Just as there would be none at all if all this New York that has so obsessed me with its limitless bigness was itself a blazing ruin.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The earthquake was crucial in the development of the University of California, San Francisco and its medical facilities.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Until 1906, the school faculty had provided care at the City-County Hospital (now the San Francisco General Hospital), but did not have a hospital of its own.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Following the 1906 San Francisco earthquake, more than 40,000 people were relocated to a makeshift tent city in Golden Gate Park and were treated by the faculty of the Affiliated Colleges.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] This brought the school, which until then was located on the western outskirts of the city, in contact with significant population and fueled the commitment of the school towards civic responsibility and health care, increasing the momentum towards the construction of its own health facilities.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In April 1907, one of the buildings was renovated for outpatient care with 75 beds.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] This created the need to train nursing students, and the UC Training School for Nurses was established, adding a fourth professional school to the Affiliated Colleges.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The grandeur of citywide reconstruction schemes required investment from Eastern monetary sources, hence the spin and de-emphasis of the earthquake, the promulgation of the tough new building codes, and subsequent reputation sensitive actions such as the official low death toll.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] One of the more famous and ambitious plans came from famed urban planner Daniel Burnham.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] But this plan was dismissed during the aftermath of the earthquake.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] For example, real estate investors and other land owners were against the idea because of the large amount of land the city would have to purchase to realize such proposals.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Limestone used to reconstruct city buildings was quarried at the nearby Rockaway Quarry.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] City fathers likewise attempted at the time to eliminate the Chinese population and export Chinatown (and other poor populations) to the edge of the county where the Chinese could still contribute to the local taxbase.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The Chinese occupants had other ideas and prevailed instead.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Chinatown was rebuilt in the newer, modern, Western form that exists today.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The destruction of City Hall and the Hall of Records enabled thousands of Chinese immigrants to claim residency and citizenship, creating a backdoor to the Chinese Exclusion Act, and bring in their relatives from China.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The earthquake was also responsible for the development of the Pacific Heights neighborhood.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The immense power of the earthquake had destroyed almost all of the mansions on Nob Hill except for the James C.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Others that had not been destroyed were dynamited by the Army forces aiding the firefighting efforts in attempts to create firebreaks.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] As one indirect result, the wealthy looked westward where the land was cheap and relatively undeveloped, and where there were better views.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Constructing new mansions without reclaiming and clearing rubble simply sped attaining new homes in the tent city during the reconstruction.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Reconstruction was swift, and largely completed by 1915, in time for the 1915 Panama–Pacific International Exposition which celebrated the reconstruction of the city and its "rise from the ashes".
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Since 1915, the city has officially commemorated the disaster each year by gathering the remaining survivors at Lotta's Fountain, a fountain in the city's financial district that served as a meeting point during the disaster for people to look for loved ones and exchange information.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The Army built 5,610 redwood and fir "relief houses" to accommodate 20,000 displaced people.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The houses were designed by John McLaren, and were grouped in 11 camps, packed close to each other and rented to people for two dollars per month until rebuilding was completed.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] They were painted navy blue, partly to blend in with the site and partly because the military had large quantities of navy blue paint on hand.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The camps had a peak population of 16,448 people, but by 1907 most people had moved out.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The camps were then re-used as garages, storage spaces or shops.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The cottages cost on average $100 to build.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The $2 monthly rents went towards the full purchase price of $50.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The last official refugee camp was closed on June 30, 1908.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Most of the cottages have been destroyed, but at least 30 survived.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Of the remaining structures, there is a historically restored pair in the Presidio.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Others have been built on as part of private homes, with a high concentration around the Bernal Heights neighborhood.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] One of the modest 720 sq ft (67 m2) homes was purchased in 2006 for more than $600,000.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] A 2017 study found that the fire had the effect of increasing the share of land used for nonresidential purposes: "Overall, relative to unburned blocks, residential land shares on burned blocks fell while nonresidential land shares rose by 1931.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The study also provides insight into what held the city back from making these changes before 1906: the presence of old residential buildings.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In reconstruction, developers built relatively fewer of these buildings, and the majority of the reduction came through single-family houses.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Aside from merely expanding nonresidential uses in many neighborhoods, the fire created economic opportunities in new areas, resulting in clusters of business activity that emerged only in the wake of the disaster.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] During the first few days after news of the disaster reached the rest of the world, relief efforts reached over $5,000,000, equivalent to $179,170,000 in 2025.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] London raised hundreds of thousands of dollars.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Individual citizens and businesses donated large sums of money for the relief effort: Standard Oil and Andrew Carnegie each gave $100,000; the Parliament of Canada made a special appropriation of $100,000; and even the Bank of Canada in Ottawa gave $25,000.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The United States Congress quickly appropriated 2.5 million dollars for relief supplies which were immediately rushed to the area, including supplies for food kitchens and many thousands of tents that city dwellers would occupy the next several years.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] These relief efforts were not enough to get families on their feet again, and consequently the burden was placed on wealthier members of the city, who were reluctant to assist in the rebuilding of homes they were not responsible for.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] All residents were eligible for daily meals served from a number of communal soup kitchens, and citizens as far away as Idaho and Utah were known to send daily loaves of bread to San Francisco as relief supplies were coordinated by the railroads.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Insurance companies, faced with staggering claims of $250 million, paid out between $235 million and $265 million on policyholders' claims, often for fire damage only, since shake damage from earthquakes was excluded from coverage under most policies.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] At least 137 insurance companies were directly involved and another 17 as reinsurers.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Lloyd's of London reports having paid all claims in full, more than $50 million, thanks to the leadership of Cuthbert Heath.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Insurance companies in Hartford, Connecticut, report paying every claim in full, with the Hartford Fire Insurance Company paying over $11 million and Aetna Insurance Company almost $3 million.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The insurance payments heavily affected the international financial system.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Gold transfers from European insurance companies to policyholders in San Francisco led to a rise in interest rates, subsequently to a lack of available loans and finally to the Knickerbocker Trust Company crisis of October 1907 which led to the Panic of 1907.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] After the 1906 earthquake, global discussion arose concerning a legally flawless exclusion of the earthquake hazard from fire insurance contracts.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] It was pressed ahead mainly by re-insurers.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Their aim: a uniform solution to insurance payouts resulting from fires caused by earthquakes.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Until 1910, a few countries, especially in Europe, followed the call for an exclusion of the earthquake hazard from all fire insurance contracts.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In the U.S., the question was discussed differently.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] But the traumatized public reacted with fierce opposition.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In the second half of 1909, the California State Legislature enacted the California Standard Form of Fire Insurance Policy, which did not contain any earthquake clause.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Thus the state decided that insurers would have to pay again if another earthquake was followed by fires.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Other earthquake-endangered countries followed the California example.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The 1906 Centennial Alliance was set up as a clearing-house for various centennial events commemorating the earthquake.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Award presentations, religious services, a National Geographic TV movie, a projection of fire onto the Coit Tower, memorials, and lectures were part of the commemorations.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The USGS Earthquake Hazards Program issued a series of Internet documents, and the tourism industry promoted the 100th anniversary as well.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Eleven survivors of the 1906 earthquake attended the centennial commemorations in 2006, including Irma Mae Weule (1899–2008), who was the oldest survivor of the quake at the time of her death in August 2008, aged 109.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Vivian Illing (1900–2009) was believed to be the second-oldest survivor at the time of her death, aged 108, leaving Herbert Hamrol (1903–2009) as the last known remaining survivor at the time of his death, aged 106.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Another survivor, Libera Armstrong (1902–2007), attended the 2006 anniversary but died in 2007, aged 105.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Shortly after Hamrol's death, two additional survivors were discovered.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] William Del Monte, then 103, and Jeanette Scola Trapani (1902–2009), 106, stated that they stopped attending events commemorating the earthquake when it became too much trouble for them.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Del Monte and another survivor, Rose Cliver (1902–2012), then 106, attended the earthquake reunion celebration on April 18, 2009, the 103rd anniversary of the earthquake.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Nancy Stoner Sage (1905–2010) died, aged 105, in Colorado just three days short of the 104th anniversary of the earthquake on April 18, 2010.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Del Monte attended the event at Lotta's Fountain in 2010.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] William Del Monte (1906–2016), who died 11 days shy of his 110th birthday, was thought to be the last survivor.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In 2005 the National Film Registry added *San Francisco Earthquake and Fire, April 18, 1906*, a newsreel documentary made soon after the earthquake, to its list of American films worthy of preservation.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Worden's gelatin silver prints documenting the destruction were later collected by the Museum of Modern Art in New York, the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art, and the Oakland Museum of California.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] After the destruction, all that remained of the Alban N.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Towne mansion on Nob Hill were six marble columns and a lintel.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] When viewed from a certain angle, the empty porch perfectly framed the ruins of the smoldering City Hall.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] The haunting image became an icon of the 1906 earthquake, due largely to photographs by Worden.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] In 1909, the columns and lintel were relocated to Golden Gate Park, where, known as Portals of the Past, they became an enduring monument to the city's grief and a symbol of its endurance.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Copyright, Pillsbury Pictures, 18 April 1906.
[src:conflagration/1906-san-francisco-earthquake] Its wood interior burned, but its steel, concrete and stone frame survived.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The **Great Kantō Earthquake** (Japanese: 関東大地震, *Kantō daijishin*, or 関東大震災, *Kantō daishinsai*) was a megathrust earthquake that struck the Kantō Plain on the main Japanese island of Honshu at 11:58:32 JST (02:58:32 UTC) on Saturday, 1 September 1923.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] It had an approximate magnitude of 8.0 on the moment magnitude scale (Mw), with its epicenter located some 100 km (62 mi) southwest of the capital Tokyo.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake devastated Tokyo, the port city of Yokohama, and the surrounding prefectures of Kanagawa, Chiba, and Shizuoka, causing widespread damage throughout the Kantō region.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The event was a complex disaster, with modern research indicating it consisted of three consecutive shocks in the span of several minutes.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The initial megathrust event in Kanagawa Prefecture was followed three minutes later by a magnitude 7.2 earthquake centered beneath Tokyo Bay, and two minutes after that by a magnitude 7.3 shock in Yamanashi Prefecture.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Fires, exacerbated by strong winds from a nearby typhoon, spread rapidly through the densely populated urban areas, accounting for the majority of the devastation and casualties.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The death toll is estimated to have been between 105,000 and 140,000 people, including tens of thousands who went missing and were presumed dead.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Over half of Tokyo and nearly all of Yokohama were destroyed, leaving approximately 2.5 million people homeless.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster triggered widespread social unrest, including the Kantō Massacre, in which ethnic Koreans and others mistaken for them were murdered by vigilante groups based on false rumors.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In the aftermath, the Japanese government declared martial law and undertook extensive relief and restoration efforts.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake prompted ambitious plans for the reconstruction of Tokyo, aiming to create a modern, resilient imperial capital under the leadership of Home Minister Gotō Shinpei.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] However, these plans were often met with political contestation, financial constraints, and local resistance, leading to a reconstruction that, while significantly improving infrastructure, fell short of the grandest visions.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster also fueled debates about national identity, modernity, and societal values, with many commentators interpreting the event as a divine punishment for perceived moral decline and advocating for spiritual and social regeneration.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Great Kantō Earthquake remains a pivotal event in modern Japanese history, profoundly impacting urban planning, disaster preparedness, and social consciousness.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] 1 September is commemorated annually in Japan as Disaster Prevention Day.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Kantō region of eastern Japan is prone to major earthquakes due to its location near complex tectonic plate boundaries.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The 1923 earthquake occurred when the Philippine Sea Plate subducted beneath the Okhotsk Plate (sometimes considered part of the North American Plate) along the Sagami Trough.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The initial shock, occurring at 11:58:32 JST on 1 September 1923, was a complex event.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Modern analysis indicates a dual rupture on a broad trench-type fault: the first rupture occurred near Odawara in Kanagawa Prefecture, some 100 km (62 mi) southwest of Tokyo, followed about ten seconds later by a second shock on the other side of Sagami Bay near the Miura Peninsula.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This was followed minutes later by two major aftershocks: a magnitude 7.2 earthquake beneath northern Tokyo Bay at 12:01, and a magnitude 7.3 earthquake in Yamanashi Prefecture at 12:03.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Survivor accounts consistently describe these three distinct seismic events.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake immediately toppled structures, crushed people, and caused widespread panic.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Survivor accounts describe an initial period of stunned silence followed by a frantic rush as people tried to reunite with family and salvage belongings.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Engineer Mononobe Nagao recalled the earth shaking "back and forth for what seemed like 15 seconds", followed by violent vertical convulsions that knocked people to the ground.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Writer Tanaka Kōtarō described the sound as akin to a giant "blackening whirlwind" churning up the earth from "deep underground".
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Within thirty minutes of the first tremor, more than 130 major fires broke out across Tokyo, particularly in the densely populated eastern and northeastern sections.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] These fires were fueled by overturned charcoal braziers used for midday meals, leaking gas from ruptured lines, and flammable debris from collapsed wooden buildings.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Strong winds, associated with a typhoon passing off the coast, fanned the flames, creating massive firestorms that swept through the city.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The air temperature in some areas reached 46 °C (115 °F).
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The combination of ongoing aftershocks and rapidly spreading fires led to pandemonium.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Millions of residents attempted to flee, often carrying their possessions, which clogged the already damaged streets and bridges.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Kawatake Shigetoshi described being trapped in a "wave of people" in eastern Tokyo, unable to move as fires approached from multiple directions.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Many sought refuge in open spaces, such as parks and the grounds surrounding the Imperial Palace, but these areas quickly became overcrowded.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Waterways like the Sumida River also became congested with boats as people tried to escape by water, only to face sparks and burning debris falling from the sky.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster quickly overwhelmed Tokyo's infrastructure and its capacity for an orderly evacuation.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Great Kantō Earthquake was one of the most destructive natural disasters of the 20th century.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Roughly half of Tokyo and virtually all of Yokohama were transformed into "blackened, corpse-strewn wastelands".
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake and subsequent fires destroyed an estimated 397,119 homes in Tokyo Prefecture alone, leaving about 1.38 million people homeless in Tokyo City.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Across the seven affected prefectures (Tokyo, Kanagawa, Chiba, Saitama, Shizuoka, Yamanashi, and Ibaraki), a total of 2.5 million people were displaced.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In addition to buildings, the earthquake buckled roads, collapsed bridges (362 destroyed and 70 heavily damaged in Tokyo), twisted train tracks, snapped water and sewer pipes, and severed telegraph lines.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Tokyo's main aqueduct from Wadabori collapsed in two places and required extensive repairs.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The sea floor in Sagami Bay dropped by over 400 meters (1,300 ft) at the epicenter, triggering tsunamis that inundated low-lying coastal communities.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Fires were the primary cause of destruction, accounting for 90 percent of the fatalities.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In Tokyo, districts like Asakusa, Kanda, Nihonbashi, Kyōbashi, Honjo, and Fukagawa were largely incinerated.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Honjo Clothing Depot, a large open area where tens of thousands sought refuge, became a death trap when a massive firestorm (a *tatsumaki* or whirlwind of fire) engulfed it, killing an estimated 40,000 people in minutes.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Survivor Koizumi Tomi described the site as "hell on earth", surrounded by "endless rows of bodies: red, inflamed bodies; black, swollen bodies; bodies partially buried under ash and smoldering remains".
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The government administration was crippled.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In Tokyo, 44 percent of the main buildings burned to the ground, including the police headquarters and the ministries of Home Affairs, Finance, Education, Communications, and Railways.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The vast majority of police stations and municipal and ward offices crumbled or burned.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Out of Tokyo's 196 primary schools, 117 were destroyed, along with numerous higher girls' schools, trade schools, colleges, and universities.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Social welfare facilities, including public dining halls, cheap lodging homes, and crèches, were annihilated.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Over 160 public and private hospitals in Tokyo were destroyed.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster exacerbated the economic downturn of the early 1920s and contributed to a genuine banking crisis in 1927.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Roughly 7,000 factories were destroyed, including major spinning, dyeing, and tool manufacturing plants.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Financial institutions suffered heavily, with 121 of 138 bank head offices and 222 of 310 branch offices in Tokyo City consumed by fire or reduced to rubble.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Insurance policies offered little relief, as most contained clauses exempting companies from earthquake-related damage; eventually, the government intervened to facilitate partial payouts.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Reconstruction brought a new surge of imports and, under these combined pressures, an early return to the gold standard was impossible.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster also led to significant unemployment.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In September 1923, the unemployment rate in the wards of Tokyo reached 45% (59% for men, 28% for women).
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By 15 November, across Tokyo Prefecture, 178,887 people were registered as unemployed, with the commerce and industry sectors most affected.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The human toll of the Great Kantō Earthquake was catastrophic.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Early estimates put the death toll as high as 140,000, but modern research based on the *1923 Great Kantō Earthquake Disaster Report* puts the total number of fatalities at 105,385.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Of these, 91,781 deaths (87%) were attributed to fires, while 11,086 (10.5%) were due to being crushed by collapsing buildings.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Other causes included drowning and landslides.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Kanagawa Prefecture suffered 32,838 deaths, while Tokyo Prefecture had 70,387.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] An additional 13,275 people remained classified as missing twelve months after the earthquake.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] People died in numerous ways: crushed by collapsing buildings, trampled in panicked crowds, burned alive in the fires, or drowned in rivers and canals while attempting to escape the flames.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Some victims suffocated as fires consumed oxygen, while others were boiled alive in ponds offering no protection from the intense heat.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The smell of burning human flesh and decaying bodies permeated the air for weeks.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Disposing of the dead became a major public health concern, leading to mass cremations, particularly at the Honjo Clothing Depot.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In the immediate aftermath of the earthquake, law and order broke down in many parts of the affected region.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This period was characterized by the spread of rumors, the formation of vigilante groups (*jikeidan*), and the massacre of ethnic Koreans and others mistaken for them, as well as the murder of political activists by the authorities.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Widespread destruction of communication infrastructure contributed to an atmosphere of uncertainty and fear.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Rumors spread rapidly, often relayed by refugees fleeing the disaster zone.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Some stories suggested that Mount Fuji had erupted or that a large tsunami had washed away Yokohama.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The most damaging rumors, however, concerned alleged activities by Koreans.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Originating from looting by Japanese in Yokohama that was misattributed to Koreans, false reports circulated that Koreans were poisoning wells, committing arson, looting, and organizing attacks on Japanese.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] These rumors were given a degree of legitimacy when some government officials, including Gotō Fumio of the Home Ministry, broadcast messages warning of "organized groups of Korean extremists" attempting to "commit acts of sedition".
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] On 2 September, the police headquarters, lacking manpower to confirm eyewitness reports, passed them on as factual and issued a statement that "unscrupulous Koreans are committing acts of arson and other forms of violence".
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Fueled by these rumors and a climate of fear and xenophobia, Japanese vigilante groups, known as *jikeidan*, formed across the Kantō region.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By mid-September, an estimated 3,689 such groups were operating, ostensibly to prevent fires, stop looting, and maintain order.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] However, many of these groups, often armed with makeshift weapons like clubs, swords, and bamboo spears, targeted Koreans and, in some cases, Chinese, Okinawans, and Japanese from certain regions who were mistaken for Koreans due to their accents.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Estimates of the death toll in what became known as the Kantō Massacre vary significantly.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Police confirmed the deaths of 248 Koreans, while an investigation by the Governor-General of Korea determined 832 had been killed or were missing.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] A separate investigation by Korean students concluded that 2,613 Koreans had been killed; some modern estimates reach as high as 6,000.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Victims were often subjected to brutal violence, including beatings, stabbings, and lynchings, sometimes after being "tested" for their Korean identity (e.g., by being asked to pronounce Japanese words that were difficult for Koreans).
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] While some police and military personnel attempted to protect Koreans, others were complicit in the violence or turned a blind eye.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Although police made belated corrections to the rumors on 3 and 4 September, few perpetrators were prosecuted; of 125 vigilante group members tried, only 32 received formal sentences, and 91 received suspended sentences.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Contemporary commentators like Hoashi Ri'ichirō and Oku Hidesaburō condemned the massacres as "extremely disgusting and internationally shameful" and a "disgraceful act that exposed a moral flaw".
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The chaos also provided a cover for the murder of political dissidents.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The most prominent case was the Amakasu Incident, in which the anarchist Sakae Ōsugi, his partner Noe Itō, and his six-year-old nephew were arrested and then brutally killed by a squad of military police led by Lieutenant Masahiko Amakasu.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake struck at a time of political uncertainty in Japan.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Prime Minister Katō Tomosaburō had died on 24 August, and Admiral Yamamoto Gonnohyōe, selected to form a new cabinet, had not yet succeeded when the disaster occurred.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster also forced the postponement of Crown Prince Hirohito's marriage and accession ceremonies.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This elite-level political vacuum contributed to confusion over who had the authority to deploy police and military personnel.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] General Ishimitsu Maomi, deputy commander of the Imperial Guard Forces, acted first, deploying troops to protect imperial locations.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Akaike Atsushi, inspector general of the Tokyo Metropolitan Police, faced an overwhelming task with outnumbered and unprepared forces.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The new cabinet was formally appointed on the afternoon of 2 September, sworn in on the lawn of the Akasaka Detached Palace amid falling ash, as other ministerial buildings were deemed unsafe.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] One of the first decisions of the new cabinet was to declare martial law over what remained of the capital on 2 September.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This ushered in the largest peacetime domestic mobilization and deployment of the army in Japan's pre–World War II history, with eventually over 52,000 troops deployed to Tokyo and Yokohama.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The martial law headquarters was granted extensive powers, including administering relief and public safety, prosecuting lawbreakers, prohibiting public gatherings, censoring information, stopping and searching individuals, and entering private homes.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Martial law remained in effect until 15 November.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Initial military deployment was fraught with difficulties.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Commanders arriving in Tokyo found a near total absence of reliable information and lines of communication were non-existent.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The military had to rely on aerial reconnaissance and around 2,000 army-trained carrier pigeons for communication.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The zone of martial law was progressively expanded to cover all of Tokyo and Kanagawa Prefectures by 3 September, and Chiba and Saitama Prefectures by 4 September.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] To counter rumors and vigilante violence, particularly against Koreans, military authorities were empowered to arrest individuals, disband suspicious groups, and confiscate weapons.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] From 4 September, military and police began to collect and transport Koreans to government-run detention centers for "protective custody"; by the end of September, 23,715 Koreans had been taken into these centers.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Yamamoto cabinet created the Emergency Earthquake Relief Bureau (*Rinji shinsai kyūgo jimukyoku*) to oversee all relief and recovery efforts.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Providing emergency medical assistance was an immediate priority, but initial efforts were largely unsuccessful.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Many organized rescue and first aid squads were unable to reach the worst-hit areas like Honjo, Asakusa, and Kanda until 4 or 5 September due to destroyed infrastructure and unofficial checkpoints by vigilante groups.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] A dearth of medical supplies, due to the destruction of numerous hospitals and dispensaries, further hampered efforts.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Relief Bureau concentrated its limited medical resources at large open areas like Hibiya Park and Ueno Park, where tens of thousands of refugees had congregated.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Over the longer term, mobile clinics and dispensaries proved most effective.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Relief Bureau created 41 units, and other organizations like Tokyo Prefecture, the Japan Red Cross Society, and the Mitsubishi Corporation also operated mobile clinics.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By 30 November, these public and private clinics had provided care to 447,111 sufferers.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Temporary hospitals, some in tents donated by American and French governments, accommodated over 6,000 seriously wounded people.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Securing food and water was a critical challenge.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Mayor Hidejirō Nagata learned on 2 September that the army's main supply depot in Fukagawa, holding 8,000 *koku* of rice (enough to feed over 500,000 people for six days), had been completely destroyed by fire.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The military managed to amass over 120,000 combat rations and 60,000 rations of rice from other stores.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By 4 September, military units were distributing dried noodles.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Eventually, 74,048 *koku* of rice were transported from military installations across Japan to distribution centers in Tokyo and Yokohama.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The government also appealed to prefectural governors for rice donations, receiving pledges of 61,490 *koku* in the first week.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] An "Emergency Requisition Ordinance" allowed the government to requisition foodstuffs and other materials.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Transporting these supplies was a major logistical challenge due to damaged rail lines and docks.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Navy personnel spent a week repairing 86 piers at Shibaura and Ryōgoku, while army forces cleared railway lines and rebuilt track.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Conservative estimates suggest that 1.25 million people received rice distributions between 6 and 10 September.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Water supply was an even more significant problem.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Tokyo's main water plant was not heavily damaged, but pipes and aquifers were severed in over two hundred locations.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Warships tanked water from Yokosuka, Osaka, and Nagoya, and the army requisitioned water barrels to transport clean water.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By the end of December, nearly 40 million gallons (151 million liters) of drinking water had been transported.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Shelter options were bleak for Tokyo Prefecture's 1.55 million homeless.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Nearly 800,000 people left Tokyo or Yokohama, first on foot and later via restricted rail service (from 11 September), to stay with relatives or friends elsewhere.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] About 250,000 people dispersed to other parts of Japan, including 17,704 to Kobe, 7,600 to Hokkaidō, and some even to Japan's colonies like Taiwan and Karafuto.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Those remaining in Tokyo flooded large open spaces such as Hibiya Park, Ueno Park, and the Imperial Palace grounds.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] On 9 September, municipal authorities began constructing temporary barracks.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Meiji Shrine site housed nearly 6,000 refugees, Ueno Park over 9,500, and Hibiya Park 7,000.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Many of these open spaces became shantytowns.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Barracks were often cramped, with an average of 0.6 *tsubo* (about 2 square meters (22 sq ft)) of floor space per person.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Sanitation was a major problem, with makeshift latrines overflowing.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] While a modest number of refugees left barrack housing by the end of 1923, many more returned to the disaster zone and erected private makeshift shacks.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By October 1923, 539,450 people were living in 111,791 such temporary abodes.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Government officials and media outlets made concerted efforts to construct the Great Kantō Earthquake as an unprecedented national calamity, requiring a unified national response.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Newspapers, the chief medium for disseminating news, played a lead role.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Major papers like the *Tokyo Nichi Nichi Shinbun*, *Osaka Asahi Shinbun*, and *Osaka Mainichi Shinbun* used emotive headlines, harrowing survivor accounts, vivid photographs, and even documentary motion pictures to convey the disaster's horror and scale to a national audience.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] These portrayals often framed the disaster in terms of wartime analogies, emphasizing themes of sacrifice and national unity.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The forty-ninth-day memorial service held on 19 October 1923, at the site of the Honjo Clothing Depot, attended by over 200,000 people and leading politicians, was a meticulously choreographed event.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Speeches by figures like Gizō Kasuya and Shōzaburō Horie explicitly linked the victims' sacrifices to the future reconstruction of Tokyo and Japan, urging national unity and effort.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Visual culture, including lithographic prints and postcards, also played a significant role in disseminating the image of a devastated but resilient capital, and of a concerned government responding to the crisis.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Postcards depicting dead bodies, while sometimes classified as contraband, were widespread and brought the human cost of the disaster to a national audience in a stark manner.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] A widespread interpretation, embraced by numerous elites across various sectors of society, was that the earthquake was an act of divine punishment (*tenken* or *tenbatsu*) or heavenly warning.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This view was not confined to religious leaders but was articulated by bureaucrats, politicians, academics, and social commentators.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster was seen as a response to Japan's perceived moral decline, materialism, luxury-mindedness, hedonism, and excessive individualism that had become prominent since World War I.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The entertainment districts of Tokyo, such as Asakusa, and centers of consumer spending, like the Ginza, were often singled out as epicenters of this perceived degeneracy and thus seen as specifically targeted by the heavens.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The destruction of icons of modern consumerism, such as the Mitsukoshi Department Store and the twelve-story Ryōunkaku tower in Asakusa, was imbued with symbolic meaning.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This interpretation served as a cosmological bolster for critiques of contemporary society and legitimated calls for social, moral, and ideological reform.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake was thus framed as a moral wake-up call, placing Japan at a crossroads between decline and renovation.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The interpretation of the earthquake as divine admonishment fueled calls for national spiritual renewal (*seishin fukkō*) and economic moderation.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] An Imperial Rescript Regarding the Invigoration of the National Spirit, issued on 10 November 1923, became a foundational document for this movement.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] It urged Japanese people to reject frivolousness, extravagance, and extreme tendencies, and to embrace simplicity, sincerity, fortitude, diligence, thrift, moderation, loyalty, and filial piety.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Government campaigns, such as the 1924 Campaign for the Encouragement of Diligence and Thrift (*Kinken shōrei undō*), employed the memory of the earthquake to promote austerity and national savings.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Policies like the 1924 luxury tariff, which placed a 100 percent duty on a wide range of imported goods deemed luxuries, aimed to curb consumer spending and foster economic self-discipline.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] While these measures had mixed results in altering consumer behavior in the long term, they reflected a broader elite concern with reorienting Japanese society towards more traditional and disciplined values.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The push for spiritual renewal also involved using schools, neighborhood associations, and new media like film and radio to inculcate desired moral values.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The devastation of Tokyo unleashed a wave of optimism among many bureaucrats, urban planners, and social reformers, who saw an unparalleled opportunity to rebuild the city as a modern, rational, and resilient metropolis.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Figures like Gotō Shinpei, Abe Isoo, and Fukuda Tokuzō argued that "old Tokyo" had been a breeding ground for social ills due to overcrowding, poor sanitation, poverty, and inadequate infrastructure.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake, they believed, created a chance to rectify these problems and construct a capital that would reflect new social values and assist the state in managing its subjects.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disorientation and destruction offered a "free field" for new ideas, but reconstruction under Gotō's direction was swift.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Many visions for the new Tokyo were influenced by "authoritarian high modernism," emphasizing state-led planning, technical and scientific progress, and intervention in many aspects of human life, from public health and housing to urban layout and transportation.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Plans called for wider, paved streets, extensive green belts and parks, modern public housing, new sanitation systems, and improved transportation networks.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Some, like Gotō Shinpei, envisioned a grand imperial capital that would project Japan's emerging power and prestige on the international stage, hoping to create a city that matched Paris and Berlin.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Despite the initial optimism, reconstruction planning was fraught with political contestation.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Gotō Shinpei, as Home Minister and head of the Reconstruction Institute (*Teito fukkōin*), championed ambitious and expensive plans, initially proposing a budget of ¥3 billion—more than twice the entire national budget at the time.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] This was met with immediate opposition from Finance Minister Inoue Junnosuke and other cabinet colleagues, who were concerned about the nation's financial stability and favored a more fiscally conservative approach.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Debates raged over the scope of reconstruction, the extent of land readjustment, the design of new infrastructure, and, crucially, the budget.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Imperial Capital Reconstruction Deliberative Council (*Teito fukkō shingikai*), an advisory body of elder statesmen and party leaders, became the site of fierce opposition.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Critics, led by Itō Miyoji, argued the plans were extravagant, could lead to financial collapse, and violated constitutional rights to ownership.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The political infighting exposed deep divisions within Japan's elite and the structural weaknesses of its quasi-democratic, bureaucratic-oligarchic political system.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Gotō's plans were progressively scaled back, with the budget reduced to ¥597 million by the council and further to ¥468 million by the Diet in December 1923.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] A key component of the physical reconstruction was land readjustment (*kukaku seiri*).
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Special Urban Planning Law of December 1923 empowered the government to rationalize irregular land plots, widen streets, and create public spaces by confiscating up to 10 percent of private land without monetary compensation.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Roughly 30,000,000 square meters (320,000,000 sq ft) of land in Tokyo were divided into 66 readjustment districts.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] While the process aimed to create a more rational and user-friendly urban environment, it was met with confusion, resistance, and numerous petitions from landowners and tenants.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Concerns involved the constitutionality of uncompensated land confiscation, the impact on businesses, the rights of tenants, and the adequacy of compensation for relocated structures.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Despite these local-level disputes, the program resulted in the rationalization of many neighborhoods, particularly in eastern Tokyo, and the creation of significant new public land for roads and other infrastructure.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Overall, about 15.3 percent of residential land in readjustment areas was converted to public use, with landowners compensated for acquisitions beyond the 10 percent threshold.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] By the time reconstruction was officially celebrated in March 1930, Tokyo had undergone significant physical changes.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The most notable successes were in transportation infrastructure.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The total area of roads in Tokyo increased by 45 percent, and many were widened and paved, with modern sidewalks.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Key arterial roads like Shōwa-dōri and Yasukuni-dōri were constructed, and new, modern steel bridges, such as the Eitai-bashi and Kiyosu-bashi spanning the Sumida River, became icons of the new city.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The river and canal system was also improved.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] However, many of the more ambitious social and environmental goals were not fully realized.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Spending on parks and green spaces, while resulting in three new large parks and 52 smaller ones, was limited.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Social welfare facilities, while improved, also received a small fraction of the reconstruction budget.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Many of the pre-earthquake urban vulnerabilities and social problems, including slum areas, persisted or re-emerged.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The final reconstruction expenditure by national and city governments totaled roughly ¥744 million.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The site of the Honjo Clothing Depot, where tens of thousands perished, became a focal point for mourning and remembrance.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Plans for a memorial were initiated soon after the disaster.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] In June 1924, the Taishō Earthquake Disaster Memorial Project Association was formed to oversee the project.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] A national design competition for the memorial complex was launched in December 1924.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The winning entry by engineer-architect Maeda Kenjirō, a 53-meter (174 ft) tower, proved controversial due to its perceived resemblance to a Prussian triumphal tower and its perceived insensitivity to Buddhist sensibilities.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] After sustained protest, particularly from Buddhist federations, the design was scrapped in December 1926.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Engineer Itō Chūta was then appointed to create a new, more "Japanese" design, heavily influenced by Buddhist architecture, featuring a pagoda that would house a charnel house.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Earthquake Memorial Hall (later the Tokyo Metropolitan Memorial Hall) in Yokoamichō Park was completed on 1 September 1930.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The Great Kantō Earthquake left an indelible mark on Japan.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] 1 September was designated as Disaster Prevention Day (防災の日, *Bōsai no hi*) in 1960, an annual commemoration involving nationwide disaster drills and awareness campaigns.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disaster highlighted urban vulnerabilities and influenced subsequent approaches to city planning and building codes, although the ideal of a truly disaster-proof city remained elusive.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The memory of the earthquake, particularly the firestorms and the Honjo Clothing Depot tragedy, continued to haunt Tokyoites, influencing their behavior even during the World War II bombings.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The events of 1923 also served as a catalyst for long-term government efforts to foster neighborhood associations (*tonarigumi*) and promote civil defense, trends that intensified in the 1930s and during the war.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The disorientation and destruction caused by the disaster marked a "significant divide" in the "massification" of culture, consumption, and taste, accelerating social and cultural changes and providing a "free field" for new artistic and radical movements.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The center of urban life in Tokyo also shifted, as the old merchant quarters of the *shitamachi* ("Low City") were particularly devastated, pushing development toward the more residential "High City" (*yamanote*).
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] Despite the significant scaling-back of Gotō Shinpei's original vision, the reconstruction provided a fine example of creative recovery, rebuilding Tokyo as a modern city and serving as a model for urban development throughout Japan until the end of World War II.
[src:conflagration/1923-great-kantō-earthquake] The earthquake and its aftermath remain a subject of historical study and public memory, serving as a stark reminder of Japan's seismic activity and the complex interplay of disaster, society, and national identity.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] The **1967 Tasmanian fires** were an Australian natural disaster which occurred on 7 February 1967, an event which came to be known as the **Black Tuesday** bushfires.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] They were the most deadly bushfires that Tasmania has ever experienced, leaving 64 people dead, 900 injured and over seven thousand homeless.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] 110 separate fire fronts burnt through some 2,640 square kilometres (652,000 acres) of land in southern Tasmania within the space of five hours.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] Fires raged from near Hamilton and Bothwell to the D'Entrecasteaux Channel as well as Snug.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] There was extensive damage to agricultural property along the Channel, the Derwent Valley and the Huon Valley.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] Fires also destroyed forest, public infrastructure and properties around Mount Wellington and many small towns along the Derwent estuary and east of Hobart.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] The worst of the fires was the **Hobart Fire**, which encroached upon the city of Hobart.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] In total, the fires claimed 64 lives in a single day.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] Property loss was also extensive with 1293 homes and over 1700 other buildings destroyed.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] The fires destroyed 80 bridges, 4800 sections of power lines, 1500 motor vehicles and over 100 other structures.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] It was estimated that at least 62,000 farm animals were killed.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] The total damage amounted to $40,000,000 in 1967 Australian dollar values.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] The resulting insurance payout was the then largest in Australian history.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] In 2017 2 more people that had died were officially recognised as victims of the bushfires, they had previously been excluded as the deaths had not been investigated by the coroner at the time.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] This took the death toll from 62 to 64 people.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] The late winter and early spring of 1966 had been wet over southeastern Tasmania, resulting in a large amount of vegetation growth by November.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] However, in November, Tasmania began its driest eight-month period since 1885, and by the end of January 1967 the luxuriant growth in the area had dried off.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] Though January was a cool month, hot weather began early in February, so that in the days leading up to 7 February 1967, several bush fires were burning uncontrolled in the areas concerned.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] Some of these fires had been deliberately lit for burning off, despite the extremely dry conditions at the time.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] Reports into the causes of the fire stated that only 22 of the 110 fires were started accidentally.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] Shortly before midday on the 7th, a combination of extremely high temperatures, (the maximum was 39 °C (102 °F)), very low humidity and very strong winds from the northwest led to disaster.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] Although this fire was by far the worst in loss of life and property in Tasmanian history, the meteorological conditions are common.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] If considered in terms of both loss of property and loss of life, in 1967 this represented one of the worst disasters to have occurred in Australia.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] It is comparable in scale with the 1939 Black Friday bushfires in Victoria (where the loss of 72 lives was spread over several days) and the subsequent 1983 Ash Wednesday bushfires in Victoria and South Australia, which claimed 75 lives and razed over 2,000 homes.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] The 2009 Black Saturday bushfires north of Melbourne, and elsewhere in Victoria, in which 173 people died, share the same commencement date of 7 February.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] Australian National University history professor Tom Griffiths has described the 1967 fires as marking the advent of a "new type" of bushfire in which suburban areas of large cities were threatened, contrasting with earlier major fires which had solely occurred in rural areas.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] A memorial for the 1967 Bushfires was built at Snug in the Kingborough municipality, south of Hobart, where a plaque with the names of the 62 people killed is fixed to a brick chimney.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] The memorial has storyboards telling the story of the 1967 fires, as well as bushfire preparedness information.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] It is surrounded by a garden of fire resistant native plants.
[src:conflagration/1967-tasmanian-fires] In 2017 2 more people that had died were officially recognised as victims of the bushfires and added to the plaque making the total 64 people.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The **2007 Greek forest fires** were a series of massive forest fires that broke out in several areas across Greece throughout the summer of 2007.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The most destructive and lethal infernos broke out on 23 August, expanded rapidly and raged out of control until 27 August, until they were finally put out in early September.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The fires mainly affected western and southern Peloponnese as well as southern Euboea.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The death toll in August alone stood at 67 people.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] In total 85 people lost their lives because of the fires, including several fire fighters.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Some of these firestorms are believed to be the result of arson while others were merely the result of negligence.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Hot temperatures, including three consecutive heat waves of over 40 °C (104 °F), and severe drought rendered the 2007 summer unprecedented in modern Greek history.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] From the end of June to early September, over 3,000 forest fires were recorded across the nation.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Nine more people were killed in blazes in June and July.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] A total of 2,700 square kilometers (670,000 acres) of forest, olive groves and farmland were destroyed in the fires, which was the worst fire season on record in the past 50 years.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Of the total of 2,700 km2, 1,500 km2 (370,000 acres) were burnt forests in Southern Greece alone which meant that 4% of Greece's total forest area burnt in 2007 alone.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Many buildings were also destroyed in the blaze.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The fire destroyed 1,000 houses and 1,100 other buildings, and damaged hundreds more.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The first major fire of the summer of 2007 was started on 28 June 2007.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] It is perceived to have been started by either an exploding electrical pylon or by arsonists.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Significant parts of the Parnitha National Park were destroyed, and in total, the fire burnt 15,723 acres (63.6 km2) of the core of the national forest in a matter of days.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Overall, the mountain of Parnitha suffered a burnt area of 38,000 acres (153.8 km2), making it one of the worst recorded wildfires in Attica since the Penteli fire of July 1995.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The magnitude of the devastation was unforeseen.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Environmental studies in Greece report that the Athenian microclimate will significantly change to warmer during the summer season, and flooding is now a very probable danger for the northern suburbs of the city.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Mount Parnitha was considered the 'lungs' of Athens; following its considerable burning, both the city and local flora and fauna are expected to feel the consequences.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Other affected areas included Pelion, Agia and Melivoia, Skourta, Dafni, and Pyli.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] On 11 July 2007, another wildfire sparked at a garbage dump near Agia Paraskevi, Skiathos, and spread across the island.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Residents and tourists were forced to evacuate to nearby Troulos, and returned after the fire was put out.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] More than 100 fires were reported by 15 July 2007, in such locations as Keratea outside of Athens, Peloponnese, and on the Aegean islands of Andros, Evia, Lesbos, and Samos, as well as Crete and the Ionian island of Kefalonia.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] In Peloponnese around 20 July 2007, a fire which started from the mountains over the town of Aigio expanded rapidly towards Diakopto and Akrata, destroyed a large area of forests and cultivated land.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] In the same fire many villages were totally or partially burned, resulting in the loss of 230 houses and 10 churches; three people lost their lives.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] A 26-year-old farmer and a 77-year-old woman were arrested on suspicion of arson concerning the fires in Aigio and Diakopto.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The farmer confessed and is currently held in prison.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Fires continued, on 17 August 2007 they started to burn on the outskirts of Athens.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Penteli began burning down towards the suburbs.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] More than sixty fire engines, nineteen planes and helicopters, and hundreds of firefighters as well as locals attempted to hold back the fire.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Melisia, Vrilisia, and Penteli city were affected in the blaze that was put out once winds calmed down.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] On 24 August 2007, fires broke out in Peloponnese, Attica and Euboea.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] In Peloponnese, the fire burnt many villages and accounted for 60 deaths.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Six people were reported to have been killed in the town of Areopoli.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] In Zacharo, one of the worst hit areas, more than 30 people were found dead by firefighters while searching burning cars and homes.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Prime Minister Kostas Karamanlis declared a state of emergency for the whole country and requested help from fellow members of the European Union.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Multiple countries responded to the call and sent help.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Additionally, 500 Greek soldiers were sent in the affected areas.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Another 500 Greek soldiers were called up bringing the total to 1,000 military personnel involved in the fire fighting.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] On 25 August 2007, fires broke out on Mount Hymettus and in the suburb of Filothei in Athens.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Officials said these fires were the result of arson, as the firefighters found many bottles with gasoline in affected areas.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Arson is also suspected for the fires in Peloponnese, as more than 20 fires started at about the same time.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Two fires broke out in Keratea and one in Markopoulo Mesogaias in East Attica on 25 August 2007.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The first fire was not under control until the following day, while the second was put out quickly.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The Keratea fire had a length of 12 kilometres (7 mi) and a man was hospitalised with second degree burns.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The fire at Lagonissi was reported as an accident, as they were started when a man accidentally set fire to a tree in his garden.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Olympia, site of the ancient Olympics and World Heritage Site, was evacuated on 26 August 2007.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Fears were expressed for the survival of the ruins of ancient Olympia lying near the raging fire.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The famous statue of Hermes of Praxiteles and nearby antiquities were spared from the fire, but the yard of the museum where the statue is housed was scorched.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] According to the official statement of former Minister of Culture Georgios Voulgarakis, no serious damage was caused to the antiquities.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The fire burnt all the trees on the hilltop above, and an area of brush and open space adjacent to the Olympic Academy.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The fire did not damage the archaeological museum nor did it damage the several ancient structures in the area.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] *"The wider archaeological space of Olympia remains intact,"* stated Mr.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Despite the Minister's claims, it has been established, as of 26 August, that the afflicted damage is of greater importance and scale; the sacred Hill of Kronos was totally burnt during the blaze.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The hill was left blackened, but will soon be reforested.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] New Culture Minister Michalis Liapis has stated that 3,200 bushes and saplings will be planted on the Hill of Kronos, to return the area to its previous appearance.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The fires continued to burn into early September.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] On 1 September 2007, firefighters were still suppressing a strong blaze in Peloponnese.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Three blazes remained, with the fires destructive path continuing in Arcadia and Mt.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Then, on 3 September 2007 a lightning strike started a new fire on Mt.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Vermion, which was soon brought under control by firefighters.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] On 5 September the death toll reached 67, and on 21 September reached 68.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] When the August fires broke out, Prime Minister Kostas Karamanlis requested help from the members of the European Union and other nations.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The former Minister for Public Order, Vyron Polydoras, stated the fires may be a result of terrorist attacks, as many of the fires started simultaneously and in places where an arsonist could not be seen.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] He also stated that the country is facing an *asymmetric threat*, a military term used for terrorist attacks.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] While some fires are believed to have been caused by environmental factors, others clearly were not.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The fires could have been deliberately started as a way to get around Greek law which forbids property development on areas designated as forest land and to pull benefit from Greece's unique position as the only EU country without a full land registry system.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] A substantial reward has been offered for anyone providing information which leads to the arrest of an arsonist.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Greek police announced the capture of three arson suspects: A 65-year-old man from Areopolis was charged with arson and murder relating to the fire which killed at least 6 in this area.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Also, in northern Kavala, two youths had been detained on suspicion of arson.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Greek government press minister Theodoros Roussopoulos confirmed on 27 August that 61 people had been arrested on suspicion of involvement in arson, seven of these being retained in custody.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] On 27 August 2007, PASOK leader George Papandreou accused the government of insinuating that his party is involved in the fires and called on Prime Minister Kostas Karamanlis to produce any evidence that would support there was such an organized plan.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] On 25 August, Super League Greece and the Hellenic Football Federation decided to postpone the opening fixtures scheduled for that weekend due to the fires.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Campaigning for the country's forthcoming general election was suspended for a short period of time.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The vote was not postponed since this is not allowed under the current Constitution.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The destruction that was caused by the fires is expected to have a large financial impact to the areas affected by the fires.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Originally the estimated amount was about 1.5 billion euros in immediate damages.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] That amount has now risen to 2 billion euros ($2.9 billion).
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The cumulative financial impact after taking into consideration the loss of national income due to the destruction of the local agricultural infrastructure and the potentially negative impact on local tourism is estimated around 5 billion euros or more.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The status of Olympia for the 2008 Summer Olympics flame-lighting ceremony is threatening to undermine the whole ceremony.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The Hellenic Olympic Committee (HOC) has warned that the delays in the reforestation process will undermine the whole ceremony.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Due to the unprecedented scale of the destruction many of the country's leading banks, businesses, institutions and local administrations have offered considerable amounts of cash in order to help the people and businesses that suffered financially due to the fires.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The government has created a special account in all Greek banks, where financial help in relief of the people affected by the fire from all over the world is accepted.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Additionally, financial aid from the EU is expected.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Forms of assistance in nature were also offered such as olive plants contributed by a Turkish municipality and businessmen to a collect already organized in Mytilene.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The Greek Government plans to spend 645.7 million euros ($946.7 million) to restore and rehabilitate areas burnt by the fires.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] This amount will be provided by both the European Union and the Greek Government.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The government has earmarked 150 million euros ($222 million) to help the people affected by the fire rebuild their homes and other buildings.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The rapid nature of the response given in the form of a direct aid scheme free of red tape led to official claims in reverse a year after the calamity, as it has been the case for the residents of Ileia who were notified to return the aid payments.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Opposition parties, in the meantime, accused the government of using the scheme to "buy" the votes of locals in the weeks before the Greek legislative election, 2007.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The Cypriot Government along with J&P ABAX have pledged to rebuild the town of Artemida.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] They have currently signed an 8.5 million euro contract, which includes the construction of 80 structures of which 48 will be residential.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The overall cost of the project is expected to be 14.5 million euro.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] On 20 February 2008 UEFA president Michel Platini presented the Hellenic Football Federation with a CHF1m cheque to help finance the rebuilding of football facilities damaged by the fires in Greece the previous summer.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The European Union has proposed 89.7 million euros in aid to Greece to offset part of the cost of the 2007 forest fires.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The grant will be used to reimburse the costs of rescue services, provision of temporary housing, cleaning up of disaster-stricken areas, and the restoration of basic infrastructures to working condition.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Furthermore, the EU created a 600-member team of European firefighters to combat continental forest fires, as a response to the 2007 summer forest fires in Southern Europe.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The Greek Government has urged regional authorities to start replanting large areas burnt by the summer forest fires.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The government under Kostas Karamanlis has pledged that all burnt forests will be restored and protected from legal development.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Full Replanting is expected to start after a reforestation study by forestry experts that is to be completed by December.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] Plans included anti-erosion measures and extensive replanting in the hardest hit prefectures of Arcadia, Achaea, Elis, Corinthia, Laconia, Messenia, and Euboea.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] The Hill of Kronos which was totally burnt by the fires will be replanted with bushes and saplings.
[src:conflagration/2007-greek-forest-fires] These bushes and saplings will include laurel bushes, oaks, olive trees, and other indigenous species.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The **Mount Carmel Forest Fire** (Hebrew: אסון הכרמל *Ason HaKarmel*, "The Carmel Disaster") was a deadly forest fire that started on Mount Carmel in northern Israel, just south of Haifa.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The fire began at about 11:00 local time on 2 December 2010, and spread quickly, consuming much of the Mediterranean forest covering the region.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] With a death toll of 44, it was the deadliest civil disaster in Israeli history until the 2021 Meron stampede.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Those killed included 36 Israel Prison Service members, most of them new recruits, as well as three senior police officers, among them the chief of Haifa's police, and three firefighters, among them a 16-year-old volunteer.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] More than 17,000 people were evacuated, including several villages in the vicinity of the fire, and there was considerable property and environmental damage.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The fire appeared to be caused by human activity near the Druze town of Isfiya.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] On 6 December a 14-year-old resident of the town told police that he had inadvertently started the fire with a nargila coal.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The teen's father argued that his son was witnessed in school at the time and could not have started the blaze.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The fire was followed by a wave of arsons throughout Israel and the West Bank.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] These fires, which initially created confusion regarding the source of the Carmel blaze, were all extinguished within a few hours of being lit.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The motivation for the attacks was not immediately clear.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Israeli police have referred to some of these fires as arson.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Government officials, including Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Foreign Minister Avigdor Lieberman, called on other countries to help assist in firefighting efforts, and the Israel Defense Forces mobilized troops for the same purpose.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The fire was defeated on 5 December after raging for 77 hours, a little over three days.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Mount Carmel contains large areas of forests, including large numbers of Aleppo pine trees, which are more easily ignited.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Over the years, many fires have occurred on Mount Carmel, among them many which devastated hundreds of thousands of acres of forest.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] One such as that was the 1989 Mount Carmel forest fire which destroyed about 3,200 dunams (320 ha; 790 acres) of forest.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Israel had been experiencing an unusually warm autumn and dry conditions; previous spring and summer months were also exceptionally hot.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] It was originally speculated that the fire was caused by the burning of an illegal garbage dump and spread due to the dry conditions and strong winds.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Haifa's Mayor Yona Yahav stated that the problem was known and it was "just a matter of time until a calamity occurred".
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Israel Police suggested that the fire was caused due to a bonfire that was lit by local residents and not extinguished properly and in time.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] However, they stressed that the investigation of the incident is in its early phases and cautioned against drawing premature conclusions.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] On 4 December, police arrested two adolescent brothers from the Druze town of Isfiya on suspicion of having caused the fire through negligence.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] On 5 December, the Haifa Magistrate Court extended the brothers' remand for three days, and on 6 December the court released them from custody under restrictive conditions.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] There were unconfirmed reports of the teens having hurled burning waste products during a picnic.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The same day, police announced that they had arrested two additional youths from Isfiya the previous night, and that more arrests could be expected soon.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] In the evening of 6 December, police announced that a 14-year-old resident of Isfiya admitted to inadvertently starting the fire.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The teen told investigators that after smoking a nargila, he threw a lit coal into an open area and was so shocked by the result that he returned to school without telling anyone what he had done.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Druze Member of Knesset Ayoob Kara, a resident of Isfiya near where the fire broke out, had said on the evening of 2 December that he had received information that the fire was a terror act.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] MKs Ya'akov Katz and Michael Ben-Ari also cited the possibility that the fire was an act of terrorism and called for an investigation.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Thirty-seven were prison service officers course cadets and their commanding officers, who were on the way to Damun Prison to evacuate its prisoners from the path of the flames.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Their bus driver also perished, as did three senior police officers, two firefighters and one teenager who was a volunteer firefighter.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] On December 4, it was announced that all of the victims had been identified.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] 36 Israel Prison Service members, of whom the majority were new recruits, died in the fire.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] After the fire started on December 2, the Damun Prison in the area of the fire called for reinforcements in order to evacuate prisoners.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] A bus carrying Israel Prison Service cadets came to assist, but caught fire on its way.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Several Police officers and a number of firefighters who were behind the bus were also injured and some were killed, including Commander Ahuva Tomer, head of the Haifa police station and the first woman to hold such a major command; Tomer suffered severe burns and died in hospital on December 6.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] A prison service cadet who was badly burned in the incident died in hospital on December 11 and a firefighter who had been hospitalized with serious burns died on December 18.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] An initial investigation showed that a tree fell down on the road, trapping the bus in a fireball.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] According to Internal Security Minister Yitzhak Aharonovich, after the vehicle caught fire, the driver was injured and lost control.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] While performing a U-turn on the narrow road the bus caught fire and the cadets tried to escape the burning vehicle.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The back door would not open due to the extreme heat but was eventually broken through, enabling some cadets to flee the burning bus; however, those who fled encountered the intense blaze outside.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] An officer and two cadets were able to escape and were picked up by a passing motorist, who then drove through the fire to safety.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Most of the IPS officers and cadets had been in their 20s and 30s, and several were Druze.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The incident is the country's deadliest single peacetime event involving security forces.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The Israel Fire and Rescue Services attempted to contain the blaze, and were assisted by Israeli volunteer firefighters and the Israel Police.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] In addition, the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) sent two battalions to assist with the extinguishing of the fire and various evacuations.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] It also sent heavy ground equipment from nearby military bases, including firetrucks, water tanks, cranes, D9 bulldozers and other equipment.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The Israeli Air Force used an unmanned aerial vehicle for reconnaissance and intelligence collection.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Use of other aircraft was prohibited because of a decade-old decision that prohibits military aircraft from being used in such a situation.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Israel requested help from various countries, including the United States.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Turkey and Greece offered to send assistance to fight the fire.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Greece was the first country to respond, sending 4 CL-415 aircraft supported by 1 C-130H with technicians and equipment to Ramat David Airbase.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Greece also sent 1 more CL-415 and 1 C-130H with firefighters the next day.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Turkey sent two firefighting aircraft, which started to extinguish fire in the early hours of December 3.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The Netherlands sent four fire extinguisher-aircraft, which could do their job as early as Monday, the 6th of December, since Benjamin Netanyahu asked the Netherlands, as well as Belgium, Germany, Finland, Norway, and Russia specifically for help.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The Swiss Air Force provided three Cougar Helicopter with fire fighting capabilities.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Cyprus dispatched a helicopter and a plane to assist in the fire-fighting effort.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Russia sent one Ilyushin Il-76 (capable of holding up to forty tons of water) and two Be-200 special firefighting planes.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Countries that offered help include Azerbaijan, Bulgaria, Croatia, Cyprus, France, Jordan, Romania, Spain with four seaplanes and the United Kingdom who sent two Royal Air Force helicopters.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Italy and Egypt also offered firefighting planes.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The Palestinian Authority sent several fire trucks to help extinguish fires near the Israeli-Arab localities of Tayibe and Barta'a; on Sunday, December 5, 21 Palestinian firefighters joined the efforts in the Carmel Forest area itself.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Senior Palestinian Authority security official Ahmed Rizek Abu Rabia said: "This is a human catastrophe.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] On December 4, the Israeli government decided to hire Evergreen's Boeing 747 Supertanker to help extinguish the blaze.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The plane landed at 01:00 at Ben Gurion International Airport.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The plane took off and at about 11:00 it released its first cargo of water.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Later in the day it made a second sortie, dropping fire retardant.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The Turkish assistance was considered surprising, due to the strain on the Turkish–Israeli relationship since the Israeli raid on a humanitarian flotilla which killed nine Turkish activists.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] At a Security Cabinet meeting, Netanyahu thanked Turkish Prime Minister Erdoğan (and others) for their offer to help, saying he "hopes this will be the beginning of better relations between our two countries".
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The fire caused widespread damage to property, as well as ecological damage.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] It initially spread very quickly because of the wind, and cut off power to houses in the vicinity.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] At least 40,000 dunams (4,000 ha; 9,900 acres) of forest were destroyed, and damage was caused to the Carmel Hai-Bar Nature Reserve.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Omri Bone, the Northern Region Director of the Jewish National Fund, estimated that 1.5 million trees burnt in the fire.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] However, another 4 million trees have reportedly burned since then.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] According to officials, nearly half of the 150,000 dunams (15,000 ha; 37,000 acres) of the Carmel Forest reserve have been destroyed in the fire.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Officials say it could take dozens of years to rehabilitate the area.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Over 17,000 people were evacuated on December 2 as a result of the fire, including 6,500 from Tirat Carmel and 3,000 from Haifa.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Villages evacuated include Kibbutz Beit Oren, Ein Hod, Nir Etzion, and the Yemin Orde Youth Village, which were severely impacted by the fire.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The University of Haifa was also evacuated, as well as three prisons (Carmel, Prison Six, and Damun) and the Tirat Carmel Mental Health Center.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Other institutions included the Carmel Forest Hotel and the Carmel Farm.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The casualty information center opened for the first time since the 2006 Lebanon War.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] In the days following the outbreak of the blaze, other fires erupted sporadically far from the main site, causing police to raise its alert level nationwide.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Investigators concluded that arsonists were attempting to "hitch a ride" on the Carmel fire.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] David Cohen stated at a press conference on 3 December that "there have been a number of arson attacks in the northern district".
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Police sources estimated that arsonists were attempting to distract forces dealing with the Carmel fire by producing additional emergency events.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] An editorial in the *Jerusalem Post* called these arson cases "homegrown terrorism".
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] A fire broke out in the Tzur Shalom industrial zone in Kiryat Bialik, forcing the evacuation of a nearby factory.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Firefighters extinguished the blaze within several hours.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Police reported finding a bicycle and a bag containing a wig near the area, increasing suspicions that arson was involved.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] A small fire that erupted in Haifa's Neve Yosef neighborhood in the afternoon was extinguished by midnight.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] A fire erupted near the northern Bedouin village of Basmat Tab'un, causing no reported injuries or damage.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] A brush fire that broke out in the Jerusalem Forest at about 13:00 burned 2.5 dunams (0.25 ha; 0.62 acres) of forest and open land.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Firefighters and police extinguished the blaze within several hours.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] After hikers nearby reported two suspects fleeing from the area where the fire started, police were treating the incident as arson and opened an investigation.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] At night, an Arab citizen of Israel and a Palestinian were arrested after allegedly trying to start a fire near Jerusalem.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The two tried to escape by car and were apprehended after a short chase.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Various fires broke out in open areas and woodland areas in the West Bank during the day, and were extinguished by Israeli and Palestinian Authority firefighters.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] One of these was a fire that broke out in a woodland area near Neve Tzuf.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The firefighting services said that the blazes were probably acts of arson.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Additional suspicious fires erupted in Kiryat Tiv'on, in the vicinity of Adi, at Route 70 by Bat Shelomo, at Beit Rimon Junction in the vicinity of Nazareth, and near Mashhad.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The Prime Minister of Israel, Benjamin Netanyahu, announced a national day of mourning, but it did not materialize.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Events celebrating of Hanukkah were canceled in Haifa.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] *The Jerusalem Post* stated in an editorial that although perhaps the only positive development of the disaster had been "the tremendous outpouring of international aid, including from the Muslim world," several copy-cat fires were later carried out by Arab Israeli terrorists.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] A few weeks after the fire, Israeli firefighters expressed disappointment with the Israeli government for not including extra money in the state budget for the next two years to bolster up Israel's firefighting capabilities.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Israel's neighboring countries both helped and criticized Israel over the handling of the fire.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Qatar-controlled Al-Jazeera pointed out that "Israel failed to contain the fire", and that it was necessary for the state to plead for international help in order to bring the blaze under control.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Various officials in European countries such as Greece, Italy and Germany reportedly also expressed their surprise at Israel's apparent helplessness.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Many asked how it was possible that a country that went through several wars could have such a significant shortage of planes and firefighting materials.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Hamas's informal 'Prime Minister' Ismail Haniyeh told Reuters in a video interview: "These are plagues from God.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The Hezbollah-run media outlet *Al-Manar* said that the fire signaled Israeli vulnerability to war and mass terrorism: "The great Carmel fire has embarrassed Israel's firefighting capabilities and proved its almost complete incompetence.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] As a result of the fire, the Israel Fire and Rescue Services adopted a new doctrine for fighting forest fires.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] On May 12, 2011, the Israeli Air Force inaugurated 249 Squadron, a new aerial firefighting unit.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] At the day of its inauguration, the unit, based at Sde Dov Airport, operated seven Air Tractor AT-802 aircraft.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] On June 20, 2012, Israel's State Comptroller Micha Lindenstrauss released his final report about the fire.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] The report found a large number of operational failures that contributed to the devastating results of the fire, and attributed special responsibility to Israel's Finance minister Yuval Steinitz and interior minister Eli Yishai.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Internal Security Minister Yitzhak Aharonovitch were also named as sharing in the responsibility for the outcome.
[src:conflagration/2010-mount-carmel-forest-fire] Lindenstrauss argued for accountability but did not demand the dismissal of any government ministers.
[src:conflagration/conflagration] A **conflagration** is a particularly large and destructive fire.
[src:conflagration/conflagration] In the environment, this may describe a fire that spreads via structure to structure, ignition due to radiant or convective heat, or ember transmission.
[src:conflagration/conflagration] Conflagrations often damage human life, animal life, health, and/or property.
[src:conflagration/conflagration] A conflagration can begin accidentally or be intentionally created (arson).
[src:conflagration/conflagration] A very large fire can produce a firestorm, in which the central column of rising heated air induces strong inward winds, which supply oxygen to the fire.
[src:conflagration/conflagration] Conflagrations can cause casualties including deaths or injuries from burns, collapse of structures and attempts to escape, and smoke inhalation.
[src:conflagration/conflagration] Firefighting is the practice of extinguishing a conflagration, protecting life and property and minimizing damage and injury.
[src:conflagration/conflagration] One of the goals of fire prevention is to avoid conflagrations.
[src:conflagration/conflagration] When a conflagration is extinguished, there is often a fire investigation to determine the cause of the fire.
[src:conflagration/conflagration] During a conflagration a significant movement of air and combustion products occurs.
[src:conflagration/conflagration] Hot gaseous products of combustion move upward, causing the influx of more dense cold air to the combustion zone.
[src:conflagration/conflagration] Sometimes, the influx is so intense that the fire grows into a firestorm.
[src:conflagration/conflagration] Inside a building, the intensity of gas exchange depends on the size and location of openings in walls and floors, the ceiling height, and the amount and characteristics of the combustible materials.
